Dear Sterling Families,
Thank you for participating in the Back-to-School survey posted last week. The results of the survey were taken into consideration in developing the attached plan that outlines the school's potential response if risk levels posed by COVID-19 increase. Please note, the most recent Southeast District Health Department risk assessment has placed Johnson County in the "low yellow" or moderate risk range and does not warrant a disruption in our school schedule. Under the currently assessed risk level, school will be in session from 8:00 AM to 3:37 PM beginning August 12th following the posted 2020-2021 school calendar. The school schedule will operate as normal at this time. The following plan is subject to change. Please contact the school if any clarification is needed.

Message from Supt. Mr. Allen,

A person at Sterling Public Schools has tested positive for COVID-19. This person has taken the necessary precautions to quarantine themselves to prevent further exposure. Sterling Public Schools will also be taking necessary precautions to ensure the safety of our students and staff by canceling summer weights and camps for the week of July 20th. I want to ensure everyone that we sanitize our weight room during and after each session to prevent the spread of germs and/or viruses. It is our goal to keep everyone safe and we will continue to err on the side of caution. If you have any questions, comments, or concerns, please contact us at school. Thank you.

NSAAHOME.ORG
Pre-Participation Physical Examinations for 2020-2021 School Year

Sterling Public Schools
April 30 at 9:52 AM ¬∑

Health care providers in the state are experiencing changing demands to deal with COVID-19. These changes are causing them to postpone most, if not all, non-essential wellness and maintenance visits. Most of them are planning changes to last until July.

The NSAA SMAC unanimously recommended to the NSAA board that Pre-Participation Physical Examinations (PPE) for the 2019-2020 school year be acceptable for the 2020-2021 seasons. This recommendation would be for a one-year exemption only and would not include incoming freshmen. They continue to recommend that students visit their primary care providers for the PPE.

To view the entire memorandum, visit the link below.

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------

What does this mean for Sterling Public Schools? The only students/athletes that will need physicals for the 2020-2021 school year will be incoming freshmen and incoming 7th graders. All other students/athletes that turned in a physical in 2019-2020 will be exempt.

post_text:
To the class of 2020... üéì

We know this year didn't end like you hoped (like any of us hoped really) but don't let that overshadow all you've accomplished during your years at SPS!

Just because there's no ceremony today doesn't mean your hard work has gone unnoticed. All the late nights doing homework, befriending underclassmen, perfecting your game, holding down a job. This is what matters. All the steps that you've taken to get to this point and beyond, those matter. This situation does not define you.

You've made impressions that will last a lifetime. We'll miss you dearly but can't wait to see what the future holds for all of you! Keep setting new goals and reaching new heights!

Sterling Parents and Families - We could use your help!

The United States Congress passed the Coronavirus Aid, Relief, And Economic Security (CARES) Act, which includes one-time relief funding for local school districts, intended to address challenges of providing education during the COVID-19 pandemic. The Nebraska Department of Education is seeking feedback from all stakeholders to understand local needs as well as potential investments and supports. Please take a moment to complete this short survey, also available in Spanish: ¬≠¬≠https://nde.qualtrics.com/jfe/form/SV_efislqh4QDEA1KZ.

Filling this form out would help provide more information to the Nebraska Department of Education regarding our needs in the rural community and possibly help provide us with funding from the CARES Act.

Deadline to complete this survey is Monday, May 11, 2020.

post_text:
Health care providers in the state are experiencing changing demands to deal with COVID-19. These changes are causing them to postpone most, if not all, non-essential wellness and maintenance visits. Most of them are planning changes to last until July.

The NSAA SMAC unanimously recommended to the NSAA board that Pre-Participation Physical Examinations (PPE) for the 2019-2020 school year be acceptable for the 2020-2021 seasons. This recommendation would be for a one-year exemption only and would not include incoming freshmen. They continue to recommend that students visit their primary care providers for the PPE.

To view the entire memorandum, visit the link below.

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------

What does this mean for Sterling Public Schools? The only students/athletes that will need physicals for the 2020-2021 school year will be incoming freshmen and incoming 7th graders. All other students/athletes that turned in a physical in 2019-2020 will be exempt.

The Nebraska State Education Association (NSEA) announced it will offer educational programming for Elementary and Secondary students that will be available free to all Nebraska children beginning Monday, March 23!

Elementary Students - Monday through Friday: 9-11AM
Secondary Students - Monday through Friday: 1-3PM

Because every family's schedule is different, all the live content will be captured and available for on-demand playback at any time!

There are multiple ways to watch this new educational programming. Families can live stream NCN at https://rivercountry.newschannelnebraska.com/teacher-tv, download the NCN app on any mobile device, or access the programming through their local cable provider, NCN on Amazon Fire, Apple TV, and Roku apps.

Visit NSEA's website at nsea.org and NSEA will provide an online forum for questions and supplemental educational resources!

Updated School Closing Information

At the recommendation of the Governor, Commissioner of Education, and Southeast District Health Department, Sterling Public Schools will close on Thursday, March 19th, 2020 temporarily as a precautionary measure to help reduce the spread of the Coronavirus. The school will remain closed until classes resume on Monday, April 6th, 2020. During this closure, the school campus will be closed to all outside personnel. Tuesday, March 17th will remain a staff only planning day with students returning for a full day of school on Wednesday, March 18th to receive educational materials for the temporary closure.

The school will remain closed until classes resume on Monday, April 6th, 2020. During this closure, the school campus will be closed to all outside personnel. Tuesday, March 17th will remain a staff only planning day with students returning for a full day of school on Wednesday, March 18th to receive educational materials for the temporary closure.

Lockdown Drill - 3/9/2020

Today the students and staff at Sterling participated in a lockdown drill to assess the districts's response to a potential intruder on campus. We believe that our schools are a safe and nurturing environment conducive for learning, but also realize that we need to have proper procedures in place. The Johnson County Sheriff's office and Sterling Fire and Rescue assisted the leadership of the district's safety team in conducting the drill and providing feedback. Sheriff Walton was impressed with how smooth and quick our students and staff carried out this drill.

The Johnson County Sheriff's office and Sterling Fire and Rescue assisted the leadership of the district's safety team in conducting the drill and providing feedback. Sheriff Walton was impressed with how smooth and quick our students and staff carried out this drill.
